Part I - (Prosper Loans Exploration)¶

by: David Akuffo-Boateng¶

Introduction¶

Prosper Loans is a Carlifornia-based peer-to-peer lending platform, where individuals can either invest in personal loans or request to borrow money. The dataset consisted of 113,937 loans with 81 variables.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loan records with 81 features. Most of these features have numerical values, but we have features which have ordered categorical values. And they are as follows:

(worst/low) ---> (best/lhigh)
EmploymentStatus: Not available, Other, Retired, Part-time, Full-time, Self-employed, Employed
IncomeRange: Not employed, 0, 1-24,999USD, 25,000-49,999USD, 50,000-74,999USD, 75,000-99,999USD, 100,000+USD
Term': 12, 36, 60
ProsperRating (Alpha): N/A, HR, E, D, C, B, AA

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  1. Features that increase the chances of getting a loan

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

ProsperRating (Alpha), LoanOriginalAmount, DebtToIncomeRatio, IncomeRange, MonthlyLoanPayment, StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginationDate, EmploymentStatus, IsBorrowerHomeowner, IncomeVerifiable, Term and ListingCategory.

Which features are best in increasing the chance of getting a loan?¶

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

No, there wasn't any unusual points

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The MonthlyLoanPayment and StatedMonthlyIncome had a long-tailed distribution with many borrowers concentrated within a range of monthly loan payments and income respectively, so we set the limit of the x axes.

Ordered features (ProsperRating (Alpha), IncomeRange, and EmploymentStatus)into categorical data type.

Set LoanOriginationDate to datetime data type.

Created a new column for year from LoanOriginationDate for analysis.

Mapped ListingCategory (numeric) to their respective descriptions for easier analysis.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, investigate relationships between pairs of variables in your data. Make sure the variables that you cover here have been introduced in some fashion in the previous section (univariate exploration).

Let's look at the pairwise realtionships between variables in the data

Features that increase the chance of getting a loan¶

Since management of Prosper started to introduce some variables from July 2009, it is prudent we filter our features of interest from July 1, 2009. This will do away with bias and give us more accurate insights from our features of interest.

In [5]:
# convert LoanOriginationDate datatype to datetime
loans['LoanOriginationDate'] = pd.to_datetime(loans['LoanOriginationDate'])
In [6]:
# filter loans from July 1, 2009
new_loans = loans.query('LoanOriginationDate >= "2009-07-01" ')
In [7]:
# create a new categories for the new dataset
ordinal_var_dict = {'ProsperRating (Alpha)': ['HR', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A', 'AA'],
                    'EmploymentStatus': ['Employed', 'Self-employed', 'Full-time', 'Part-time', 'Retired', 'Other', 'Not available'],
                   'IncomeRange': ['Not employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999',  '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+'],
                   'Term': [12, 36, 60]}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    new_loans[var] = loans[var].astype(ordered_var)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Borrowers who took large amount of loans generally had a higher Propser Rating

Borrowers with high Stated Monthly Income had a higher Prosper Rating.

Borrowers with higher Monthly Loan Payment had higher Prosper Rating.

Borrowers who were employed, self-employed or worked full-time had higher monthly incomes.

Most Borrowers who took loans are employed, and most of them had higher Prosper Ratings, with C-rating having the largest number of borrowers.

Loan Original Amount and Monthly Loan Amount had a strong positive correlation; which obviously meant that the higher the loan original amount, the higher the monthly loan payment.

Debt Consolidation was the most popular listing category among borrowers, and with that C-rating had the highest number of borrowers.

Debt to Income Ratio is inversely proportional to Prosper Rating; meaning the lower a borrower's debt to income ratio, the higher the prosper rating and chance of getting the loan.

Loan Original Amount had weak positive correlation with Stated Monthly Income, according to the Pearson Correlation coefficient. This meant there was a slight chance that the higher a borrower's monthly income, the larger amount of loan that borrower requested.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

On a fore-sight, one would think 25,000USD-49,999USD income range will have the highest number of prosper ratings, especially C-rating, since that income and C-rating had the highest number of borrowers for income range and prosper rating respectively. It was observed that income range of 50,000USD-74,999 had the highest number of C-rating.

Income range of 25,000USD-49,999USD had the highest number of borrowers who earned that amount, and also, borrowers who are employed had the highest number among the employment status. However, among the borrowers who are employed, there were more borrowers who earned an income range of 50,000USD-74,999USD.

Conclusions¶

We can clearly see factors that increased the chances of getting a loan.and these were;

  1. Be employed
  2. Have a low debt to income ratio
  3. Have a loan original amount of not less than 4000USD
  4. Have a monthly income of not less than 5000USD
